05945nam a22006135i 9780804779197DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20022003cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047791977 a10.1515/97808047791972doi  a(DE-B1597)581913  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aPOL0120002bisacsh00aAsian Security Order :bInstrumental and Normative Features /ced. by Muthiah Alagappa. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2002] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (656 p.) :b2 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tTables and Figures -- tPreface -- tAcronyms and Abbreviations -- tContributors -- tIntroduction: Predictability and Stability Despite Challenges -- tPart I. Conceptual Perspective -- t1. The Study of International Order: An Analytical Framework -- t2. Constructing Security Order in Asia: Conceptions and Issues -- t3. Sovereignty: Dominance of the Westphalian Concept and Implications for Regional Security -- tPart II. Pathways to Order -- t4. Incomplete Hegemony: The United States and Security Order in Asia -- t5. Balance-of-Power Politics: Consequences for Asian Security Order -- t6. Regional Institutions and Asian Security Order: Norms, Power, and Prospects for Peaceful Change -- t7. Track 2 Diplomacy: Ideational Contribution to the Evolving Asian Security Order -- t8. Economic Interdependence and Economic Cooperation: Mitigating Conflict and Transforming Security Order in Asia -- t9. The UN System as a Pathway to Security in Asia: A Buttress, Not a Pillar -- tPart III. Management of Specific Issues -- t10. Acute Conflicts in Asia After the Cold War: Kashmir, Taiwan, and Korea -- t11. Territorial Disputes and Asian Security: Sources, Management, and Prospects -- t12. Maritime Issues in Asia: The Problem of Adolescence -- t13. Nuclear Weapons, Missile Defense, and Stability: A Case for "Sober Optimism" -- t14. Managing Internal Conflicts: Dominance of the State -- t15. Human Security: An Intractable Problem in Asia -- tPart IV. Conclusion -- t16. Managing Asian Security: Competition, Cooperation, and Evolutionary Change -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMore than a decade has passed since the end of the Cold War, but Asia still faces serious security challenges. These include the current security environment in the Korean peninsula, across the Taiwan Strait, and over Kashmir, the danger of nuclear and missile proliferation, and the concern with the rising power of China and with American dominance. Indeed, some experts see Asia as a dangerous and unstable place. Alagappa disagrees, maintaining that Asia is a far more stable, predictable, and prosperous region than it was in the postindependence period. This volume also takes account of the changed security environment in Asia since September 11, 2001. Unlike many areas-studies approaches, Alagappa’s work makes a strong case for taking regional politics and security dynamics seriously from both theoretical and empirical approaches. The first part of this volume develops an analytical framework for the study of order; the salience of the different pathways to order is examined in the second part; the third investigates the management of specific security issues; and the final part discusses the nature of security order in Asia.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Security (National & International).2bisacsh1 aAcharya, Amitav, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlagappa, Muthiah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlagappa, Muthiah, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aAnwar, Dewi Fortuna, econtrib